<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Seeds of <i>Arctostaphylos morroensis </i>germinate with heat from fire, but heat is not necessary for germination. Greenlee and Langenheim (1990) estimate historic fire intervals for the ecologically similar Monterey Bay area to be 10 to 100 years. However, moderately long fire return intervals (around 100 years) appear to support <i>A. morroensis, </i>and deviation from the natural fire regime may favor this obligate-seeding species (Van Dyke et al. 2001). In the long absence of fire, <i>Quercus agrifolia </i>increases in the mesic chaparral stands, which can gradually develop oak canopies at the expense of the shrubs (Griffin 1978).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (50-100+ years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
